description: React component composition, state management, and code style guidelines for the flowstate frontend
globs: "*.tsx, *.ts"
alwaysApply: false
---

## Component Composition

- Keep components small and single-purpose. If a component exceeds ~80 lines of JSX, split it.
- Separate **container** components (data fetching, state, side effects) from **presentational** components (props in, JSX out).
- Compose via props and children, not deeply nested internal logic. Prefer passing data down over reaching up.
- No index.tsx barrel files. Import components directly by their file path.

## File & Naming Conventions

- **Files**: kebab-case (`message-bubble.tsx`, `chat-input.tsx`)
- **Components**: PascalCase exports (`export function MessageBubble()`)
- **Hooks**: `use-` prefix, kebab-case file (`use-mobile.ts`)
- **Props**: Define a `Props` interface (or inline type) at the top of the file. Keep prop surface area minimal.

## Directory Structure

```
src/
  components/
    chat/          # Feature-specific components
    sidebar/       # Feature-specific components
    ui/            # Shared shadcn/ui primitives only
  stores/          # State management (context + reducer)
  hooks/           # Custom hooks
  lib/             # Types, utilities, API client
```

- Group components by feature, not by type.
- `ui/` is reserved for reusable design-system primitives (shadcn/ui). Do not put feature logic here.

## State Management

- Global state lives in `stores/app-store.tsx` via React Context + `useReducer`.
- Access state with `useApp()`. Mutations only via `dispatch`.
- Keep local UI state (input values, toggles, expanded/collapsed) in `useState` at the component level.
- Streaming/real-time state (`streamingTurns`) is kept separate from persistent session data.
- State updates must be immutable. Always create new objects/Maps; never mutate in place.

## Styling

- Tailwind CSS utility classes only. No CSS modules, no styled-components, no inline `style` objects.
- Use the `cn()` utility from `lib/utils` for conditional/merged classes.
- Theme via CSS custom properties defined in `index.css`. Reference with Tailwind's `var()` syntax.
- shadcn/ui components for all standard UI primitives (Button, Tooltip, DropdownMenu, etc.).

## TypeScript

- All components must be typed. No `any` unless absolutely unavoidable.
- Shared domain types live in `lib/types.ts`. Keep this file as the single source of truth for backend-mirrored types.
- Discriminated unions for messages and events (use `type` field). Match with exhaustive `switch/case`.
- Props interfaces colocated with the component, not exported unless reused.

## Hooks & Effects

- `useEffect` cleanup is mandatory for subscriptions, listeners, and async operations. Use a `cancelled` flag for async effects.
- Prefer `useRef` for values that don't trigger re-renders (scroll positions, mutable tracking flags).
- Custom hooks go in `hooks/`. Extract a hook when the same stateful logic appears in 2+ components.
- Do not create hooks for one-off logic that only exists in a single component.

## Patterns to Follow

- Functional components only. No class components.
- Callbacks passed as props use clear verb names (`onSend`, `onInterrupt`, `onSelect`).
- Comments only where intent isn't obvious from the code. No JSDoc on simple props or obvious functions.
- Radix UI primitives for accessibility. Use semantic HTML and aria attributes.
- Controlled inputs: component owns its value via `useState`, calls parent callback on submit.

## Anti-patterns to Avoid

- Monolithic components that handle data fetching, state, and rendering in one file.
- Prop drilling more than 2 levels deep. Extract a context or restructure the component tree.
- `useEffect` for derived state. Use `useMemo` or compute inline.
- Premature abstraction. Three similar lines is fine; don't create a helper until the pattern repeats meaningfully.
- Direct DOM manipulation outside of refs for measurement/focus.
